nd consent, unintended consequences, and hegemonic forms influence the ongoing rotation of migrant workers. This captivating account of the labor market as 'invisible cage' breaks new ground in Middle East and migration studies alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Developing & Emerging Countries.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107042040 cprintz978080475825340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362700040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503627000423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503627000/original  a978-3-11-070420-4  Stanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles